  "text": "The LibreOffice Calc formula evaluation chain for a formula like =SUM(A1:A10) involves several key components:\n\n1. **Formula Parsing & Compilation (compiler.cxx)**: When a formula is entered into a cell, the `ScCompiler` class (declared in sc/inc/compiler.hxx, implemented in sc/source/core/tool/compiler.cxx) tokenizes the formula string into a token array. This involves lexical analysis to recognize function names (SUM), operators, cell references (A1:A10), and other formula elements, converting them into an internal token representation optimized for evaluation.\n\n2. **Formula Cell Storage (formulacell.hxx/formulacell.cxx)**: The compiled formula token array is stored in a `ScFormulaCell` object (declared in sc/inc/formulacell.hxx, implemented in sc/source/core/data/formulacell.cxx). This class represents a spreadsheet cell that contains a formula. It holds the compiled token array, the cached formula result, and manages dependency tracking and recalculation state. The cell implements methods like SetDirty() to mark itself as needing recalculation when dependencies change.\n\n3. **Bytecode Interpretation (interpr*.cxx files)**: When a formula cell needs evaluation, the `ScInterpreter` class (declared in sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx, implemented across multiple files sc/source/core/tool/interpr1.cxx through interpr8.cxx) evaluates the token array. The interpreter maintains an evaluation stack, processes each token sequentially, and evaluates functions like SUM by iterating through the specified range and accumulating values. Each interpr*.cxx file handles different categories of functions:\n   - interpr1.cxx: Spreadsheet/array functions\n   - interpr2.cxx-interpr8.cxx: Additional function categories (database, datetime, financial, text, logical, information, math functions)\n\n4. **Recalculation Scheduling (formulacell.cxx & document.cxx)**: The `ScRecalcMode` enum (defined in include/formula/tokenarray.hxx) specifies when a formula should be recalculated (NORMAL, ALWAYS, FORCED, ONREFMOVE, etc.). When a cell's precedents (dependencies) change, the `ScDocument` class (in sc/source/core/data/document.cxx) broadcasts notifications that trigger dirty-marking of dependent cells via the ScFormulaCell::SetDirty() method. The document maintains recalculation state and controls the overall recalculation cycle through methods like DoRecalc() and DoHardRecalc().\n\nThe complete evaluation chain: Formula String → ScCompiler (tokenization) → ScFormulaCell (storage & dirty tracking) → ScInterpreter (bytecode evaluation) → Result cached in ScFormulaCell, with dependency tracking managed by ScDocument's recalculation system."
}

